webwork.pg-code:
$a = 3;
$d = 5*10+8;
Context("Fraction");
$xsq = Fraction("$d/$a");
Context("LimitedRadical");
$x0 = Formula("sqrt($xsq)");
$answer = List("$x0, -$x0");
$pos = sqrt($xsq);
Context("Numeric");
$approx = List("4.40, -4.40");

solution.p:
Because the variable we want is squared, we use extraction of roots. First, we multiply both sides by 3 to clear the fraction.
\begin{aligned}[t] \alert{3}V \amp = \alert{3}\left(\frac{1}{3} \pi r^2h\right)\\ 3V \amp = \pi r^2h \amp\amp \blert{\text{Divide both sides by } \pi h.}\\ \frac{3V}{\pi h}\amp= r^2 \amp\amp \blert{\text{Take square roots.}}\\ \pm\sqrt{\dfrac{3V}{\pi h}}\amp= r \end{aligned}
Because the radius of a cone must be a positive number, we use only the positive square root: r = \sqrt{\dfrac{3V}{\pi h}}.

subsection.p:
Equations of the form
    \blert{a(px + q)^2 + r = 0}
    can also be solved by extraction of roots after isolating the squared expression, (px + q)^2.

solution.p:
First, we isolate the perfect square, (x - 2)^2.
\begin{aligned}[t] 3(x - 2)^2 \amp = 48 \amp\amp\blert{\text{Divide both sides by }3.}\\ (x - 2)^2 \amp = 16 \amp\amp\blert{\text{Take the square root of each side.}}\\ x - 2 \amp = \pm\sqrt{16} = \pm 4 \end{aligned}
This gives us two equations for x,
\begin{aligned}[t] x - 2 \amp =4 \amp\amp \text{or }\amp x - 2 \amp =-4\amp\amp\blert{\text {Solve each equation.}}\\ x \amp=6 \amp\amp \text{or }\amp x \amp =-2 \end{aligned}
The solutions are 6 and -2.

